@node chip "LTC 1090/1290"

This chip allows measuring voltages with a resolution of 1024 or 4096 steps.
The module I use (Conrad Electronic) has a LT 1021-5 for a precise 5V reference.
It is connected to the handshake pins of you serial port where it also gets
the current it needs (don't worry, just 2 mA).
This program uses the RTS, DTR and CTS signals to communicate with the module.
Regarding the software, you don't need to know if you have the 10 or the 12 bit
AD converter, the results are always in the same range, you'll just notice
that the values the 10 bit chip sends are always dividable by 4.

Messie is compatible with the original Conrad kit regarding the used
hardware.

@endnode

@node abstract "Overview"

About this program

This program was designed to control the @{"LTC 1090/1290" link chip} using the
serial port of your Amiga. It allows to record 8 channels up to one value per
second. On my A4000-EC030 it then uses about 10% CPU, so it maybe can
completely block slower machines. But normally you don't need 8 channels
at once, you can run it in the background.

main features are:

- recording is done using a high-priority background task. Your normal
  work should not prevent Messie from recording data just like you wanted.
  
- writing is buffered for minimum disk access. 8 channels once per second possible 
  even when using floppies.

- the output files are named automagically using date and channel number.

- you can insert comments at any time.

- all functions can be accessed using AREXX for automatic programmable recording

- flexible @{"design" link design}, so you can easily fit Messie to your needs.

- font-sensitive and resizable GUI


Note: it is NOT designed to record more than one value per channel and second.

@endnode


@node requirements "What you need"

Requirements

Software:

This program should run on any Amiga with OS 2.0 or higher, no MUI required.
If you have locale.library you can use the german catalog or design one
in your favourite language using the .cd file.

I could not yet test it with OS 1.3, but it should exit with an error
message (no guarantee).

If you want to modify the program you need a C++ compiler.

Hardware:

The AD converter I use is based on the @{"LTC 1090/1290" link chip}.
It is one of those do-it-yourself kits from Conrad Electronics, Germany,
for a price of about DM 70,-

@{b}EVEN IF YOU DON'T HAVE THIS@{ub} converter, you maybe can use my
little program. Just find someone who re-writes one short section of simple
C-code (about 150 lines), you can keep the rest.
Fitting the program to a different hardware should be no problem at all,
when I wrote it I was still not sure which port it would use.

Since I have to bang on the hardware, this program will maybe not work
with future Amigas (I hope there will be any...).
Correct me if you know how to program the handshake pins without direct
use of the CIAs.
@endnode


@node usage "How to use it"

Configuration

The general settings can be adjusted using the command line or tooltypes.

 WORKDIR:

 The directory where Messie will create one subdirectory per day,
 and in each subdirectory files for the data and the comments.
 example: 

        WORKDIR="work:"

 LOCATION:

 Whatever you like, for example 

        LOCATION="Glue and Hammer Hardware, Soldertown"

 Will just be written to the header, nothing else.

Command line options will override the tooltypes.

The GUI

 The meaning of the START and STOP button should be clear...
 When you hold down the shift key, you can start/stop all channels at once.
 Using the slider gadget or the cursor keys you can select the channel for
 which the interval settings should be changed or for which you would
 like to save a comment.
 Hitting return in the integer/string gadget will do the job.

 Note: starting/stopping channels, setting the interval will automatically
 create a comment.

AREXX commands

 The portname of the AREXX port is
 
        MESSIE
 
 The currently supported command pattern is:
 
 "START/S,STOP/S,CHANNEL=CH/K/N,INTERVAL=INT/K/N,COMMENT=COM/K,LOCKGUI/S,UNLOCKGUI/S"
 
 Nota bene:
 Since AREXX strips the " from your comment strings, you will have to enclose them
 in an additional pair of ', like
 
 cannel 1 comment '"One two three"'

 An example says more than a thousand words:
 
 --------------- cut here ---------------------------
 
 /* Testscript for Messie */

 address command
 
 run Messie
 
 waitforport MESSIE

 address MESSIE

 lockgui

 do i = 0 to 3
  ch i int 2
  ch i com '"AREXX testscript - fast"'
 end

 do i = 4 to 7
  ch i int 4
  ch i com '"AREXX testscript - slow"'
 end

 start

 address command wait 5 mins

 stop

 unlockgui
 
 quit

 --------------- cut here ---------------------------

 This AREXX program will start Messie, lock the user interface of Messie,
 all gadgets will be ghosted. Then the channels 0 to 3 will be set to an
 interval of 2 seconds, the rest will be set to 4 seconds.
 All channels will be started then, and after 5 minutes they will be stopped
 and the GUI will be unlocked again, Messie will quit.

 If you have any questions or suggestions, don't hesitate to ask @{"me" link author}

@endnode


