@node purpose "Why this program exists"

My father bought the Conrad Electronic AD converter kit for some hobby
astronomers (Walter-Hohmann-Sternwarte Essen e.V.). He wanted to do some
radio astronomy. The original software for IBM compatibles was next to
unusable for this job, there was a high speed recorder which got the data
from the module as quick as possible and a bad-written GW Basic program
to demonstrate how to program it. (© Bernd Kunze 20.2.1994)
See @{"design" link design} for details.
I had mercy with him after watching him drive to the observatory several times
just because he wanted to start the program for recording data during the night.
I could not understand why a whole PC should be blocked just for writing one
line to a file every 3 seconds or so, so at last I decided to write a program
which is multitasking friendly and makes automatic recording possible.

Here it is.
Maybe it is quite some overkill for this simple job, but as soon as I had
started programming I wanted to do this job well.

@endnode

@node design "Why I did it this way."

@{b}Speed@{ub}

At first this program needed next to no CPU time, but it did not work.
It was too fast for the converter, I changed the signals and this lame
chip did not notice that at all... I had to insert little delay routines
between each bit transfer, using timer.device which is quite CPU time
consuming and gives me more delay than I actually need.
If you have a better idea, tell me.

@{b}File format@{ub}

In the first column there are the seconds since midnight. I chose
this format for the time because you can convert it quite easily to whatever
you think is better, and you can plot the datafiles using a normal plot
program like gnuplot or mulitplot. In the comments files you'll always
find the date in the normal AmigaOS format aswell, just for readability.

@{b}C++@{ub}

Maybe you wonder why I used C++ for this program, not simple C.
The reason is simple: I wanted to learn C++.
The main problem was to connect the AmigaOS-Functions (C) with
the rest of my program (C++). I think I did it far from perfectly,
but it works...

I encountered some trouble when I wrote the communications stuff
between the main program and the daughter-task, this part is not
very elegant but it works... Maybe I'll re-write that later.

The sources:

See the includes for description of the different classes.

The data recording is done by a process which runs in the background and which
does no I/O operations which could force it to stop.

If the program does not seem to react in any way, it is most likely just writing
data to disk. This is done sychronously, but normally you should not remark it
at all, unless you are using floppy disks.

This program was written using g++ using libnix, it should be possible to
recompile it with another compiler without major problems...
I get no warnings using -Wall -pedantic.

Trying the Storm C/C++ demo from Aminet, I get a lot of VERY
strange error messages, no idea why.

@endnode


@node future "Que sera, sera..."

Bug of V1.0: Just before I released that version, there was a small harmless
change I did not test. It would have been harmless, if I had not forgotten two
parantheses at a very critical point. (Did not compare the result of a function
to zero, but its address "if(foo()) <-> if(foo)". Silly mistake.
The program did not work, but no one complained about that. Users, if you are
out there, please send me an email! Yes, you! If there is no one using it,
I can save the time for documentation and uploads.

Maybe it would be nice to have a cute little iconify gadget like KCON windows,
but I am not sure how to write this in a system friendly way.

NO, there will be no MUI interface.

If your Amiga is faster than mine, and the program does not read correct values,
it might be that your machine is too fast. This problem can be solved easily,
see karte.cc

"The documentation files all have the suffix '.cc'" (anonymous)

Do you have suggestions?
@endnode


